  1. We would like to convert the temperature from Farenheit to Celsius. Below are several attempts to do so that each fail.

    Try running each expression in R. Record the error message in a comment Explain what it means. Be sure to directly relate the wording of the error message with the problem you find in the expression. (1 pt)

(temp -32)

There isnt an error, but this isnt the proper formula to convert to celsius.

(temp - 32)5/9

A. Error: unexpected numeric constant in (temp - 32)5
B. R doesnt know what to do with the 5 following the ). There should be some type of operator connecting the parenthetical expression and the 5.

5/9(temp - 32)

A. Error: attempt to apply non-function
B. R thinks that we are using 9(temp - 32) as a function, i.e.that there is some function called 9(). (Is this even possible?). Again, we should have some operator between the 9 and the parenthetical expression.

[temp - 32]5/9

A. Error: unexpected [ in [
B. [] is used for indexing objects, such as object[1]. Is there an object called before the [] in this code?

  1. Provide a well-formed expression that correctly performs the calculation that we want. Assign the converted values to tempC. (1 pt)
tempC <- (temp-32)*(5/9)

  1. Generate a vector called normsamps containing 100 random samples from a normal distribution with mean 2 and SD 1. (1 pt)
normsamps <- rnorm(100,2,1)
  1. Calculate the mean and sd of the 100 values. (1 pt)
mean(normsamps)
## [1] 2.105607
sd(normsamps)
## [1] 0.9008781
  1. Use implicit coercion of logical to numeric to calculate the fraction of the values in normsamps that are more than 3. (1 pt)
mean(normsamps>3)
## [1] 0.15

  1. Look up the help for rnorm. You will see a few other functions listed. Use one of them to figure out about what answer you should expect for the previous problem.

    That is, find the area under the normal(2, 1) curve to the right of 3. This should be the chance of getting a random value more than 3. What value do you expect? What value did you get? Why might they be different? (1 pt)

1-pnorm(3,2,1)
## [1] 0.1586553
pnorm(3,2,1,lower.tail = FALSE)
## [1] 0.1586553

I would expect it to be close to 0.15, but it can be a little off because I only sampled 100 observations, so my sample distribution is going to be slightly different than the true population distribution.

You can also notice that we are asking what proportion of observations fall 1 standard deviation above the mean, which is approximately 16%.
